## Java Solution

```java id="’wini94r"
class Solution {

    List<Integer> ans = new ArrayList<>();

    public List<Integer> inorderTraversal(TreeNode root) {

        inorder(root);

        return ans;
    }

    public void inorder(TreeNode root){

        if(root == null)
            return;

        inorder(root.left);

        ans.add(root.val);

        inorder(root.right);
    }
}
```

---

## Recursion Flow

Consider the tree:

```text id="’wini94s"
        1
       / \
      2   3
```

Function calls happen like this:

```text id="’wini94t"
inorder(1)

│
├── inorder(2)
│      ├── inorder(null)
│      ├── Visit 2
│      └── inorder(null)
│
├── Visit 1
│
└── inorder(3)
       ├── inorder(null)
       ├── Visit 3
       └── inorder(null)
```

Every recursive call performs the **same three steps**:

1. Traverse left.
2. Visit current node.
3. Traverse right.

---

## Complexity Analysis

| Operation             | Time Complexity |
| --------------------- | --------------- |
| Visit every node once | O(n)            |

**Time Complexity:** `O(n)`

Reason:

* Every node is visited exactly once.

---

**Space Complexity:** `O(h)`

Where `h` is the height of the tree.

* Balanced Tree:

```text id="’wini94u"
O(log n)
```

* Skewed Tree:

```text id="’wini94v"
O(n)
```

The extra space is used by the recursion call stack.

